  <p class="osos-note">Sagamok's own <a href="https://www.sagamokanishnawbek.com/chief-council" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Chief and Council page</a> lists twelve Councillors alongside the Chief. The staff directory spells one name "Micheal Abitong" where the Chief and Council page spells it "Michael Abitong"; both entries describe the same Land-Based Resource Instructor role at Saswin. <a href="/about#corrections">Tell us if we have this wrong</a> and we will correct it.</p>

  {% include 'components/section_heading.html.twig' with { title: 'The principle' } only %}
  <blockquote class="osos-quote">
    "Chief and Council&hellip; oversee the work of the organization."
    <cite>Sagamok Anishnawbek, <a href="https://www.sagamokanishnawbek.com/chief-council" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Chief and Council page</a></cite>
  </blockquote>
  <p>A councillor helps set the budgets, approves the spending, and oversees the managers of the administration. When that same councillor is also an employee of the administration, they are on both sides of the table: overseeing the very body that employs and pays them. This is not a question about any one person's work. It is a question about the structure.</p>

  {% include 'components/section_heading.html.twig' with { title: 'The ask' } only %}
  <div class="osos-ask">
    <p><strong>Choose one.</strong> A member of Chief and Council should hold one paid public role: keep the elected seat, or keep the staff job. One public role each. This changes nothing about a person's standing in the community. It simply separates the people who oversee the Nation's money from the people the Nation pays.</p>
  </div>

  {% include 'components/section_heading.html.twig' with { title: 'Right of reply' } only %}
  <p>Chief and Council have been asked directly to confirm this information is current and to submit any corrections. Any correction they provide will be reflected here.</p>

